                    <msContents>
                        <summary>Lüġatnama</summary>
                        <textLang mainLang="ota" otherLangs="lat gre chg arm ukr ron">Ottoman
                            Turkish, Latin, Greek, Chaghatay, Armenian, Ukrainian, and
                            Romanian</textLang>
                        <msItem xml:id="MS_Marsh_187-item1" n="1">
                            <title key="">Lüġatnama</title>
                            <title xml:lang="ota" key="">لغات نامه</title>
                            <author key="person_14870437">
                                <persName xml:lang="ota">Ali Ufkî, 1610-1675</persName>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota-Latn-x-lc">علی افقی</persName>
                            </author>
                            <note>A comparative vocabulary of Latin, Modern Greek, Ottoman Turkish,
                                a Kipchakised variety of Chaghatay (described as "Tatarice"),
                                Armenian, Ruthenian (described as "Slavonice seu Russice"), and
                                Wallachian/Romanian/Arumanian words arranged in seven columns,
                                beginning with Latin on the left side, and concluding with
                                Wallachian on the right. In some places the Greek is omitted. The
                                Latin words only are arranged in alphabetical order.</note>
                            <note>Clackson and Vaux (2018) established that Albertus Bobovius,
                                a.k.a. Ali Ufkî (1610-1675), was the actual author of the
                                dictionary. <persName key="person_89029165">Ralph
                                    Cleminson</persName> (personal correspondence) suggests it was
                                possibly the result of a desire to supplement his edition of
                                Calepinus with six languages not in the original.</note>
                            <note>The section labeled 'Tartarice' appears to be in a sort of
                                post-Classical Chaghatay heavily influences by a spoken variety of
                                Kipchak Turkic. Nandriș (1957) asserts that the Wallachian elements
                                are best described as Arumanian or Macedono-Romanian. Svoboda (1956)
                                labels the 'Slavonice' elements a type of early Ukrainian, whereas
                                    <persName key="person_69152682569823312349">Agata
                                    Pawlina</persName> (personal correspondence) suggests that
                                'Ruthenian' is a more appropriate label until such time as the
                                dialectal features of the material can be assessed more
                                thoroughly.</note>
                            <listBibl>
